properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow beginning this afternoon changing to rain Wednesday. Snowfall total: 5 to 10 cm. Rainfall total: 20 to 40 mm. Location: northeastern New Brunswick. Remarks: A warm front moving westward off the Gulf of St. Lawrence will bring snow to New Brunswick beginning this afternoon. Precipitation will change to rain on Wednesday as temperatures rise above zero. An extended period of rain is then expected to last until Thursday night, when temperatures should fall below zero again. At this time, precipitation should change to flurries and taper off by Friday morning. Temperatures will remain above freezing through the overnight hours on Wednesday. The rain and mild temperatures could lead to significant melting of the snow pack and runoff. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NBStorm.
Expires: 2020-04-01T06:43:07-00:00

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Heavy rain on the way for mid week. Rainfall totals: 15 to 35 mm. Location: northern and eastern Nova Scotia including Cape Breton. Time span: Wednesday and Thursday Remarks: Rain will begin on Wednesday morning as a warm front passes westward through the Gulf of St. Lawrence and into New Brunswick. This rain could persist through the day on Thursday. Heaviest rainfall amounts are expected along the eastern shore of Nova Scotia and eastern Cape Breton Island. The rain, combined with mild temperatures may cause significant melting of any remaining snowpack and runoff. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NSstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NSStorm.

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snow beginning Tuesday morning changing to rain Wednesday morning. Snowfall total: 2 to 5 cm. Rainfall total: 15 to 30 mm except possibly exceeding 40 mm over Prince County. The rain and mild temperatures may lead to significant melting of the snow pack and runoff. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. properties.Title: Freezing Rain Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Freezing rain is expected or occurring. Freezing rain fell early this morning in the Saskatoon area, causing icy road conditions, then at 7 a.m. it changed over to snow. Radar shows this area of freezing rain tracking east-northeast towards Melfort, Wakaw, and Humboldt. It will likely produce icy roads before transitioning to snow by early this afternoon. Wynyard plus areas east and south of there should receive mostly rain from this system. ### Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become icy and slippery. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to SKstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #SKStorm.
